        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "An axion, a pseudo-Nambu-Goldstone boson introduced by Wilczek  [1] and Weinberg [2], arises in the Peccei-Quinn solution of the strong CP problem [3]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 55,
                    "end": 62,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "text": "Wilczek"
                },
                {
                    "start": 64,
                    "end": 67,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 81,
                    "end": 84,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "[2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 147,
                    "end": 150,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Even though the original axion model [1,2] was ruled out by laboratory experiments, KSVZ (Kim-Shifman-Vainstein-Zakharov) [4,5] and DFSZ (Dine-Fischler-Srednicki-Zhitnitskii) [6,7] invisible axion models are not excluded by terrestrial experiments or astrophysics considerations [8].",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 37,
                    "end": 40,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 40,
                    "end": 42,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 122,
                    "end": 125,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 125,
                    "end": 127,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "5]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 175,
                    "end": 178,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 178,
                    "end": 180,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "7]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 279,
                    "end": 282,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "One of the most sensitive techniques for detecting axions suggested in Ref. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "[9] was searching astrophysical",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[9]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Email address: hyunsulee@ibs.re.kr (H.S. Lee) 1 Present address: Department of Physics, Carleton University, Ottawa, Ontario, K1S 5B6, Canada objects such as a Sun that would constitute an intense source of the axions (solar axions). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 46,
                    "end": 47,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "1"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 5,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Email",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The solar axions are expected to be produced in the Sun via following process [10],",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 78,
                    "end": 82,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Compton scattering: \u03b3 + e \u2192 e + a",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 2,
                    "end": 9,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Compton",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Axio-recombination: e + A \u2192 A \u2212 + a",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Axio-deexcitation:",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Axio-bremsstrahlung: e + A \u2192 e + A + a",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 Electron-electron collision: e + e \u2192 e + e + a where e is an electron, a is an axion and A is an atom. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The total axion flux on the surface of the Earth produced from the Sun was estimated in Ref. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "[10] and is shown in Fig. 1 (a).",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 4,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[10]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 21,
                    "end": 31,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1 (a)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In this paper, we present results from a solar axion search performed with the COSINE-100 experiment [11,12,13]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 101,
                    "end": 105,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 105,
                    "end": 108,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "12,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 108,
                    "end": 111,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "13]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A data set corresponding to 59.5 days exposure with 106 kg of low background NaI(Tl) crystals was analyzed. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "We consider the axions that are produced in the Sun and propagate to the Earth. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "We restrict the search to axion mass m a < 1 keV/c 2 which matches the validity range of the flux calculations [10].",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 111,
                    "end": 115,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Axions may give signals in detectors through their coupling to photons (g a\u03b3 ), electrons (g ae ), and nuclei (g aN ). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The coupling g ae can be observed via scattering off the electron of the NaI(Tl) crystals through the axioelectric effect [14,15,16,17,18], a + A \u2192 e + A + where A is either a Na or I atom. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 122,
                    "end": 126,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[14,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 129,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "15,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 129,
                    "end": 132,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "16,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 132,
                    "end": 135,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "17,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 135,
                    "end": 138,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "18]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The cross section for axio-electric interactions [17,18] is,",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 49,
                    "end": 53,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "[17,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 53,
                    "end": 56,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "18]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "where E a is the axion energy, \u03c3 pe is the photoelectric cross section for either Na or I [19], g ae is the axionelectron coupling, \u03b2 a is the axion velocity over the speed of light, \u03b1 is the fine structure constant, and m e is the electron mass. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 90,
                    "end": 94,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b18",
                    "text": "[19]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The cross section in case of g ae = 1 for both Na and I atoms is shown in Fig. 1 (b).",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 74,
                    "end": 84,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1 (b)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "COSINE-100 is a dedicated experiment to test an observation of annual modulation in the event rate observed by DAMA/LIBRA experiment [20,21] utilizing a 4 \u00d7 2 array of NaI(Tl) crystals with a total weight of 106 kg located at the Yangyang underground laboratory. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 133,
                    "end": 137,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "[20,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 137,
                    "end": 140,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b20",
                    "text": "21]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The crystals are immersed in 2,200 L of linear alkyl benzene (LAB)-based liquid scintillator (LS), which acts as a veto for multiple hit events [22]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 144,
                    "end": 148,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b21",
                    "text": "[22]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Shielding structures of copper, lead, and plastic scintillator surround the liquid scintillator to reduce the background contribution from external radiation and to veto cosmic-rays [11,23] as shown in Fig. 2. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 182,
                    "end": 186,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 186,
                    "end": 189,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b22",
                    "text": "23]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 202,
                    "end": 208,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Data from the two-month period between 20 October 2016 and 19 December 2016 are used in this analysis. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This period was very stable with no environmental abnormality.",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Each of the eight NaI(Tl) crystals is coupled with two high quantum efficiency photomultiplier tubes (PMTs), R12669SEL selected for high quantum efficiency, Hamamatsu photonics. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "An event is triggered when coincident single photoelectrons in both PMTs from a single crystal are observed within a 200 ns time window. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "If an event is triggered, waveforms from all eight crystals are recorded during 8 \u00b5s windows around the hit. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The eight crystals are named crystal-1 to crystal-8. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Six crystals have light yields of approximately 15 photoelectrons/keV so that 2 keV analysis thresholds can be applied. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "However, two crystals, crystal-5 and crystal-8, have lower light yields and present 4 keV and 8 keV analysis thresholds, respectively [11,12]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 134,
                    "end": 138,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[11,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 138,
                    "end": 141,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The energy calibration was done with 3 keV X-rays from 40 K and 46.5 keV \u03b3-rays from 210 Pb, which are internal background radiations in the crystal.",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Because of low cross-section for solar axion interactions, a solar axion interacts at most only once while traversing the COSINE-100 detector. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Therefore, the solar axion search dataset requires: a signal in one crystal and no signal in any other crystals, the liquid scintillator or the muon detector. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Events with hits in other crystals or the liquid scintillator are selected as multiple-hit events and used for the development of event selection criteria, energy calibration, efficiency determination and background assessment as described in Refs. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "[12,24,25]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 4,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[12,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 4,
                    "end": 7,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b23",
                    "text": "24,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 7,
                    "end": 10,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b24",
                    "text": "25]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Multivariate machine learning algorithms, Boosted Decision Trees (BDTs) [26], are trained to discriminate PMT-induced noise events from radiation induced scintillation events. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 72,
                    "end": 76,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b25",
                    "text": "[26]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Multiple-hit events produced by Compton scattering of \u03b3-rays from a 60 Co calibration source, weighted to match the energy spectrum of the expected background, were used as a scintillation signal sample. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 32,
                    "end": 39,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Compton",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Single-hit data were used as a training sample containing both the scintillation signals and PMT noise. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "A description of the variables used for the training is given in Ref. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "[27].",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 4,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b26",
                    "text": "[27]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The efficiencies of the selection criteria are determined with the multiple-hit events from the 60 Co source data and are consistent with those measured using the multiple-hit events in the data sample that contains 3 keV 40 K peaks as described in Ref. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "[12]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 4,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "On average, a 70 % selection efficiency at 2 keV is obtained for the low-threshold six crystals.",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The predominant backgrounds in the solar axion search region of interest (ROI) are \u03b3 and \u03b2 radiation produced by radioactive contaminants internal to the crystals or on their surfaces, from external detector components, and cosmogenic activation. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "These backgrounds are modeled using the Geant4 [28] based detector simulation described in Ref. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 47,
                    "end": 51,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b27",
                    "text": "[28]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 40,
                    "end": 46,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "Geant4",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "[24]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 4,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b23",
                    "text": "[24]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Several sources of uncertainties in the background model are included in this analysis. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The largest uncertainties are those associated with the efficiency, which include statistical errors in the efficiency determination with the 60 Co calibration and systematic errors derived from the independent crosschecks. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Uncertainties in the energy resolution and nonlinear responses of the NaI(Tl) crystals [29] as well as 210 Pb modeling [24] are accounted. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 87,
                    "end": 91,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b28",
                    "text": "[29]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 119,
                    "end": 123,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b23",
                    "text": "[24]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 3 shows the comparison of the measured energy spectrum and the estimated one using the simulated events with their as-  We generate solar axion interactions in the COSINE-100 detector setup using the solar axion flux and cross sections discussed in Section 1. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_3",
                    "text": "Figure 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The generated events produce the signals through the COSINE-100 detector simulation, and the simulated events are analyzed using the same selection criteria that are applied to the data. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "In Fig. 3, the simulated solar axion energy spectra for m a = 0 keV/c 2 and m a = 1 keV/c 2 for g ae = 1\u00d7 10 \u221210 are overlaid on the measured background spectrum of crystal-7. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 3,
                    "end": 9,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_3",
                    "text": "Fig. 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "No distinct differences for the two ax-  ion masses are seen. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "We, therefore, use only two axion masses to describe axion signals between m a =0 keV/c 2 and m a =1 keV/c 2 .",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "To estimate the signals induced by solar axion, we do a binned maximum likelihood fit to the measured energy spectrum, which is given by",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "where, N ch is the number of crystals, N bin is the number energy bins, N bkg is the number of background components, N syst is the number of systematic nuisance parameters, n i j is the number of observed counts and \u00b5 i j is the total model expectation by summing all N bkg background components and a solar axion signal component after application of a shape change due to N syst systematic effects. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "In the first product of Gaussians, x k is the amount of the k th background component, \u03b1 k is the mean of x k and \u03c3 x k is its uncertainty. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "In the second product of Gaussians y l is the l th systematic parameter and \u03c3 y l is its uncertainty. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "All crystals are fit simultaneously. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The Bayesian Analysis Tookit [30] is used with probability density functions that are based on shapes of the simulated solar axion signals and the evaluated backgrounds. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 29,
                    "end": 33,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b29",
                    "text": "[30]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "As seen in the formula, a linear prior for the signal is applied. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The means and uncertainties of the Gaussian priors for the various components of the backgrounds are determined from the model fitted to the data [24]. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 146,
                    "end": 150,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b23",
                    "text": "[24]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "To avoid biassing the axion search, the fitter has been tested with pseudo experiments. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "For each axion mass, we performed 1,000 simulated experiments with the expected backgrounds and no axion signals included. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "From this procedure, we calculate the expected 90% confidence level (CL) limits.  ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 69,
                    "end": 71,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "CL",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 4: (color online) The summed energy spectrum of the six crystals (black points) is shown with the best fit for m a = 0 keV/c 2 (blue solid line) overlaid with \u00b11\u03c3 (green) and \u00b12\u03c3 (yellow) shaded region of the systematic uncertainties in the background model. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Figure 4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "For the comparison with the possible signal shape, we inserted a solar axion signal assuming g ae =4 \u00d7 10 \u221211 (red dotted line). ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The lower panel shows the residuals between the data and the best fit, normalized to the best fit.",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Data fits are performed for two selected solar axion masses: m a = 0 keV/c 2 and m a = 1 keV/c 2 . ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "An example of a maximum likelihood fit with m a = 0 keV/c 2 is shown in Fig. 4. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 72,
                    "end": 78,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "For both masses (0.0 keV/c 2 and 1.0 keV/c 2 ), the data fits found no excess of events that could be given by solar axion signals in our data. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The posterior signal probabilities were consistent with zero in both fits. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "We determine 90% CL limits of the axion-electron coupling, g ae < 1.70 \u00d7 10 \u221211 for m a = 0 keV to 1 keV and exclude QCD axions heavier than 0.59 eV/c 2 in the DFSZ model and 168.1 eV/c 2 in the KSVZ model. ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 17,
                    "end": 19,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "CL",
                    "resp": "whitelist",
                    "id": "software-simple-w5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 5 shows the observed 90% CL limit with the \u00b11\u03c3 and \u00b12\u03c3 bands from pseudo-experiments.  ",
            "section": "COSINE-100 setup and data",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
